David,

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt; I've been told that treaties constitute the highest level of American law.
&gt; Is this true?
">

I'm not sure what "highest level" means here. The US is not famous for
honoring it's treaty agreements, so probably not. Pres. Jackson's
administration was sued in the Supreme Court for not honoring a treaty with
some indians. The indians won, Jackson ignored the court.

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt; Assuming it to be true, suppose that a US president were to enter into a
&gt; treaty with multiple foreign nations to form one large, combined country.
&gt; The goal being to create a large US based supernation (like the EU).

&gt; Would the US electorate have any recourse against such a treaty?  Would
&gt; such
&gt; a treaty require ratification of Congress?
">

The executive branch negotiates treaties. The treaties then must be
ratified by Congress. This is part of the checks and balances system.
Since there is no court that really has the armies necessary to enforce
such treaties, the electorate can repudiate a treaty by electing people who
won't honor the treaty.
And this happens. So the US is not regarded as a country that can be
trusted to honor it's word.

Good luck,
Dave M.
