<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt; I've been told that treaties constitute the highest level of American law.
&gt; Is this true?

&gt; Assuming it to be true, suppose that a US president were to enter into a
&gt; treaty with multiple foreign nations to form one large, combined country.
&gt; The goal being to create a large US based supernation (like the EU).

&gt; Would the US electorate have any recourse against such a treaty?  Would such
&gt; a treaty require ratification of Congress?
">

The US Constitution at Article VI Section 2 states that "the laws of
the United States which shall be made in Pursuance thereof, and all
Treaties made, or which shall be made, under the Authority of the
United States, shall be the supreme law of the land..."

The Constitution at Article II Section 2 states that "He [the
President] shall have Power, by and with the the Advice and Consent of
the Senate to make Treaties, provided that two thirds of the Senators
present concur..."

The Constitution at Article V states that " The Congress, whenever two
thirds of both Houses shall deem it necessary, shall propose
Amendments to this Constitution, or, on the Application of the
Legislatures of two thirds of the several States, shall call a
Convention for proposing Amendments, which, in either case, shall be
valid to all intents and purposes, as part of this constitution..." To
date, there has not been a constitutional convention in the US since
1787, and all amendments have been the result of the congress
proposing them and the states ratifying them.

The question that you present, in essence, is what happened
historically with the United States after the Revolutionary War was
over in 1781 and before the present Constitution was adopted in 1789.
Each of the former colonies -- Virginia, Maryland, New York, etc. --
was a separate country with separate money, customs duties, weights
and measures, etc. and organized in a loose confederation of states
with a weak "national" government. The system proved unworkable and a
constitutional convention was called to tweak the system. The result
was the adoption of the present constitution.

Many of the questions that you ask were debated in the 1780's in the
United States with parties for and against the present constitution.
The fears were the same (of a strong central government crushing the
rights of the states). Ultimately our founders adopted the model that
we have today. Other instances in US history which parallel your
question occurred when the US made the Louisiana Purchase, the War
with Mexico, the purchase of Alaska and the Annexation of Hawaii, each
of which involved the use of treaties to add territory that was either
purchased or conquered from a foreign power. The people of the United
States embraced these moves through the actions of Congress.

There are many good resources on this period of US history which may
be useful -- google "Articles of Confederation", "US Constitution
history", "US Constitution". The book "The Federalist Papers" is also
a good resource.

Good Luck.

Mike Boersma
