Not just "such a treaty" and, instead, all treaties (that are that)
are subject for their effectiveness to an affirmative vote agreeing to
and implementing them of two thirds of the U.S. senate:

" [The president] shall have Power, by and
with the Advice and Consent of the Senate,
to make Treaties, provided [sic] two thirds of
the Senators present concur . . . ."

U.S. Constitution, Art. I, Sect. 2. cl. 2

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt; Would the US electorate have any recourse against
&gt; such a treaty?
">

The answers to this question depend on whether the question uses the
word "electorate" as if a synonym merely/solely for (in effect if not
in these exact words) "persons eligible to and/but acting only by a
vote" as distinguished from voters and would-be voters in general (the
"electorate"?) acting in what might be a variety of political
organizing and speech related and other political ways (e.g., "Lets
vote the S.O.B.s out if they agree to this!" radio call-in talk show
campaigns and political rallies, etc.), also on whether (as has of
course occurred in U.S. history) the electorate will have persuaded a
substantial number of senators to use the senate's constitutionally
granted "advice and consent" prerogative to persuade the president not
to negotiate the treaty in question in the first instance or, at
least, not to approve it by the required two-thirds vote if the
president negotiates and provisionally agrees to the treaty in
question anyway, and, in any event, what one would regard as
"recourse" in other ways (e.g., the electorate influencing congress to
use its power of the purse as a means not to fund activities otherwise
required by a treaty).

There are numerous examples in the history of the United States
including comparatively recently in which, presumably in response to
perceived electorate opposition, the U.S. senate convinced a president
not to try to enter into a contemplated treaty and also refused to
vote to approve a treaty after having been presidentially negotiated.
