The poster is of course correct that, as a significant matter of U.S.
constitutional history, the reference to Reid v. Covert (and, for that
matter, Reid's progeny) ought not be overlooked.  But this ought not
prevent the analytically minded from also recalling that, as a matter
of basic logic, the quoted excerpt from Reid is a classic example of
circular question begging:  The U.S. constitution's  Art. VI, which
expresses that constitution's "all Treaties made, or which shall be
made, under the Authority of the United States, shall be the supreme
Law of the Land" requirement, is of course itself a key part of that
instrument and, as such, it also contains its own qualification
addressed exactly to what might be otherwise claimed to be "restraints
of the Constitution" found elsewhere in that instrument - i.e., that
otherwise validly entered into and U.S. senate voted treaties are to
be "supreme" in law "anything in the Constitution or laws of any State
to the contrary notwithstanding."

