This article is a limitation on the rights of the *States*.  It provides
that no State may repudiate a treaty entered into by the federal
government.  It is not intended to imply any hierarchy of federal
legislation.

The right of the *people* to approve or reject federal treaty agreements
is elsewhere explicitly invested in the Senate.

As for judicial revue, though the Supreme Court has never ruled an
entire treaty unconstitutional, most scholars accept that it would have
the same power over treaties that it exercises over statutes -- that the
two are equal in that regard.

See here for a brief discussion:
http://supreme.justia.com/constitution/article-2/19-constitutional-li...
or http://tinyurl.com/2wlhpn .
--

