In what case was the United States sued?  In _Worcester v. Georgia_
the Supreme Court overturned the state convictions of several people
for living in Indian country without a state permit.  President Jackson
famously noted that Chief Justice Marshall would have a harder time
enforcing the decision -- against the state of Georgia -- than making
it.  The Wikipedia page on the case claims, with citation, that Jackson's
actual statement was "The decision of the supreme court has fell still
born, and they find that they cannot coerce Georgia to yield to its
mandate."

The 19th century Indian cases are probably obscure to foreigners
and of negligible concern to 21st century negotiators.  A more
famous treaty that was made in the lifetime of some people still
living established the League of Nations.  President Wilson was
the driving force behind the League but the Senate repudiated
his agreement.

