The US was not a party to that treaty, because the Senate refused to
ratify it.  The Constitution specifies that the Senate has that
power.

This is not the same as "repudiating" a treaty, which would be the
international equivalent of "anticipatory breach of contract," where
you announce that you will no longer abide by the terms of a treaty
you have agreed to in the past.  The US had not "agreed to" the LoN
treaty because a vital step -- ratification -- had not occurred.
